## post 1
hen I started my first SaaS company, I absolutely hated the idea of selling.

I tried everything to avoid it. 

I even tried to force a credit-card-only signup flow just so I wouldn't have to talk to prospects.

But I quickly learned a brutal truth: if you want to scale ARR, win sticky customers, and get top sales talent to trust your company, you have to get great at selling first as a Founder.

After I sold that first company, ToutApp (backed by a16z), to Marketo, I joined their executive team as SVP of Strategy. We did a two-year transformation, and I was part of the team that sold Marketo to Adobe for $4.75bn.

Since then, I started Unstoppable (a GTM advisory firm that has helped hundreds of AI and SaaS companies win) and today I run TK | Capital - a HoldCo with a portfolio of AI, SaaS, and advisory companies.

Over my career, I've closed millions in ARR. 

The Founder-led sales playbook I run maintains a 50%+ win rate. Even after I recruited salespeople and plugged them into the exact same system, they continued to see a 50%+ win rate.

On today's Unstoppable Sunday episode, I'm breaking down the 3 core principles inside my Founder-Led Sales Playbook:

1. Never Go Outbound: In 2026, outbound is a losing game. AI inboxes filter it out, and you lose all your leverage. Get them to book with you instead. (Plus, my 1A rule: Delete the meeting immediately if they don't match your ICP).

2. Never Sell (Ask Why They Booked Instead): Sales isn't about convincing; it's about clarity. Approach every call like a diagnostician. 

3. Never Give a Generic Demo: Ask deeply personalized questions first. Prospects don't care about your robust features; they care about their specific outcomes.

Look, I get it. 

If you're a technical founder or an early-stage builder, hopping on sales calls can feel incredibly icky. You’re afraid of sounding like a sleazy used-car salesman pushing something people don't need.

But once you shift the frame from "convincing" to "clarity" and approach calls from a place of pure service, everything changes. 

You don't just close more deals... you actually start to love the process.

In today's episode, I also share a critical bonus principle I learned from old-school sales legend Frank Swain on exactly how to budget your call time to guarantee a signed proposal or a clear next step.

Stop running a sloppy, stressful sales process. 

